From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sun, 21 Jun 2026 07:06:44 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] xargs: resolve children against the logical cwd, drop the
 unshare hack
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Per the architecture rule "no unshare; use logical state": the xargs builtin
no longer runs on a worker thread that `unshare(CLONE_FS)`+`chdir`s to give
itself a per-thread kernel cwd. xargs doesn't traverse — it only spawns
children — so the logical cwd is pure launch state: the vendored fork gains
`XargsIo::cwd()` and sets it as each spawned child's `current_dir` (exactly
like the env/nice/... exec-wrappers materialize logical state at spawn). The
builtin now runs in-process on the calling thread with no cwd manipulation;
`catch_unwind` preserves the old panic isolation the thread provided.

This removes the cross-thread cwd race and the silent-wrong-dir / fail-loud
handling the previous commit added for xargs — there is no longer any process
cwd to get wrong. Verified: `cd /tmp/xt && find . | xargs cat` and
`echo x | xargs -I{} pwd` both run children in /tmp/xt with the engine's
process cwd untouched.

(find still uses the per-thread mechanism; its walkdir traversal is
AT_FDCWD-coupled and must keep printing relative paths, so de-unshare-ing it
needs the fork's walk rooted at the logical cwd — a separate, larger change.)

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01B5MwFcipu6iwqtMPPwFhXd
---
 src/xargs/mod.rs | 15 +++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 15 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/xargs/mod.rs b/src/xargs/mod.rs
index edf2e71..cf4fc4f 100644
--- a/src/xargs/mod.rs
+++ b/src/xargs/mod.rs
@@ -49,6 +49,14 @@ pub trait XargsIo {
     fn child_stderr(&self) -> Option<Stdio> {
         None
     }
+    /// Working directory for spawned children. An embedder returns `Some(_)` to
+    /// run each child in the shell's LOGICAL cwd (so relative input items and the
+    /// command resolve there) without the in-process engine ever changing its own
+    /// process cwd. The default `None` inherits the process cwd, matching the
+    /// standalone binary.
+    fn cwd(&self) -> Option<&std::path::Path> {
+        None
+    }
 }
 
 /// The dependencies used when xargs runs as the real standalone executable:
@@ -488,6 +496,13 @@ impl CommandBuilder<'_> {
 
         let mut command = Command::new(entry_point);
 
+        // Run the child in the shell's LOGICAL cwd (in-process embedder), so
+        // relative input items and the command resolve against the box's cwd
+        // without the engine touching its own process cwd. No-op for standalone.
+        if let Some(dir) = io.cwd() {
+            command.current_dir(dir);
+        }
+
         if let Some(replace_str) = &self.options.replace {
             // Replace all occurrences in initial args with the extra arg,
             // Thanks to `MaxArgsCommandSizeLimiter`, we only process a single extra arg here.
